author: HARRY from FSTRVL TRVOSE, PA

author: Catherine from BROOMALL, PA

author: Dvora from Tucson, AZ

author: Christopher from HOMESTEAD, FL

instruction: The repair was relatively simple: Remove all the screws/fasteners with a nut driver. Separate the door liner from the door frame. Remove the old gasket. Fit the new gasket to the door liner and align with the holes in the door frame. Replace the screws.

author: Paul from SUDBURY, MA

title: Refrigerator not cooling, freezer thawing but cold.
instruction:
I removed the back lower panel within the freezer compartment. The cooling fan which draws cold air from the evaporator unit was functioning fine. I then unplugged the unit.
The evaporator unit was frozen in a block of ice. I removed all food contents from both the freezer and the refrigerator, moving them to a back-up refrigerator.

title: No flame. Igniter cold.
instruction:
Unplugged the machine. Removed the front cover by removing the 2 Philips screws near the bottom of the front of the machine. Unplugged the igniter. Replaced it. Put this all back together.
Note: Fire will not stay on while front cover is off or door is open.

author: Michael from PRESCOTT, AZ

author: Michael from PRESCOTT, AZ

author: Jennifer from VANCOUVER, WA

author: frank from GRAND ISLAND, FL

Turn off ice maker
Slide wire harness shield off connector
Disconnected harness
Loosened 2 wall screws
Remove old ice maker
Installed new one reversing process

Pull refrigerator from wall and disconnect the water line and unplug the power.

author: Daniel from DENHAM SPGS, LA

author: Albert from SAN ANTONIO, TX

author: Laurence from San Diego, CA

Check ends of each water line

title: Ice Maker Can’t Rotate/Discharge Ice

First, remove power to the refrigerator.

To replace the ice maker you first have to remove the back mounting assembly, which ice maker is attached to.

Only three Phillips head screws need to be removed: 2 on the bottom and 1 on the back of the ice maker mounting assembly. Do not remove the two diagonal Phillips head
author: Paul from CLEARFIELD, UT

title: The refrigerator ice maker needed replacing

Then reversed the steps in replacing the refrigerator ice maker kit assembly. It took slightly over 30 minutes to remove and replace the ice maker.

author: Thomas from HUNTSVILLE, TX

author: Bryan from ADA, MI

Six screws to remove the old one (I looked up the process on Youtube) and six screws had it back in tip top shape.

author: JOHN from BARDSTOWN, KY

instruction: This was a very easy repair. First, remove the Ice Bucket off the refrig door. Unfasten the white plastic shaft holder held in place by 2 hex head screws using a nut driver. author: Don from BELLVILLE, TX

author: Gary from Palm Coast, FL

instruction:
The heavy work is moving the fridge, then take off the lower plans. Use a bowel or cup for screws and the water line connector spacers so you don't loos them.
undo connections holding water line, including the bottom brakes for the solenoid. Reuse the spring around the lower waterline to prevent external wear on the line.

title: Water leaking from back of the refrigerator
instruction:
Pretty simple fix.

1) Removed the screws from lower back plate
2) Removed the screws holding the plastic water lines in place (little plastic brackets - several of them)
3) Take a picture of how the tubing and what hose goes into what part - the 5/16" hose can go into 2 different spots - I didn't do this and I had to
author: Jason from PLEASANT HILL, CA

title: Changing out the Ice Maker tube
instruction:
An easy way to get a refrigerator out from the wall is to use a tow strap or 1/2 to 3/4 in. rope. Throw a loop behind refer while keeping both ends in your hands. Let it settle down to the lower half of unit and pull using both hands. Comes right out.
Remove lower panel. Unscrew water valve from cabinet. Remove all tube holders L
author: HARRY from SPARKS, NV

title: Water feed line running from water valve to filter housing was leaking
instruction: Shut off water supply. Disconnect main supply line. Remove rear lower panel on back of refrigerator. Remove all tubing clamps on back. Disconnect leaking tubing from water supply valve. Remove water filter and unscrew/remove water filter housing. Replace tubing - connect to water filter housing then to water supply valve. Reconnect filter
author: Tom from EASTON, PA

title: Broken water line
instruction: Remove water filter and water filter holder. Removed cover on back of frig. Removed clip where water line connects to back of water filter. Took half inch wrench pushed in on water line lock to release line. Repeat at other end. Reverse steps to put on new line. Easy repair.
author: Debbie from FISHER, AR

title: Leak in water filter supply line
instruction: I found a crack in the pex line from the valve up the back of the refrigerator to the water filter. I could not find the correct 5/16" size line locally to replace it. A guy in plumbing at Home Depot said he always repaired them by cutting out the crack and finding a piece of clear vinyl line that would fit tightly over the cracked pex
author: John from Pacific, MO

author: Ray M from Cave Creek, AZ

author: Richard from STATEN ISLAND, NY

author: James from Aubrey, TX

author: Laura from Ashaway, RI

author: Scot from Fort Collins, CO

Placed new handle in position and used same tools on same screws to attach to door.

3 rescrew those screws in
4 tell your kid to stop slamming the fridge door shut

author: Eric from EXETER, NH

Refrigerator door shelf bin snapped into place with no problem.

author: Bob from St. Louis, MO

author: Carolynn from CASTLE ROCK, CO

author: Debbie from Mount Juliet, TN

There were two small round studs in each slide track missing from the originals. Since there were no corresponding holes in the metal shelf bracket on my fridge, I ground off the plastic studs with a Dremel tool and the tracks fit perfectly.

author: Robert from MANSFIELD, MA

author: Danielle from DUBLIN, OH

author: Ben from Lansdale, PA

instruction: Remove sliding drawer. Remove glass shelf. Inspect the installation slots that the support rail is mounted through. author: larry from Purdon, TX

instruction: Remove both crisper pans and covers. Discard old frames and re-use glasses. Use two screw drivers to gently pry out broken supports. Top broken off smooth on one support. author: John from JASPER, TX

instruction: My wife discovered the Parts Select website. I searched for and found our model number, found what I thought was the part I needed, called and the very professional lady confirmed I was correct. author: Frank from Orange Park, FL

title: Water Dripping from through the door water outlet and Ice Maker doesn't make ice.
instruction:
I had two problems, the first was that water was dripping from the through the door outlet and the second problem is that the ice maker wasn't making ice.

Replacing the water valve was a simple process:

1. Turn off the water to the fridge at the household shutoff valve.
2. Move the fridge away from the wall.

instruction: pulled out the old assy and replace with the new one.

title: old gasket mold and torn
instruction: Pull out old one from right top. Wipe track with a cloth and some Windex. Wipe with clean cloth place gasket over where it will replace old. Start right top push into track. Time 10 minutes once all seated again go over the entire gasket check all in track push with thumb easy replacement!!
author: Derek from MALIBU, CA

title: Refrigerator was freezing food on the bottom shelves
instruction:
It was simple. I pulled out the old seal from the track it was tucked in and put the new one in using a wood spatula to help along the folding part of the door that fits behind the other door. I replaced both seals under 15 minutes. I am a 63 year old female so I know if I can do it so can you!
Tip: make sure that you line up the to
author: Lyndi from LEBANON, TN

title: Ice build up in freezer because of hard gasket.
instruction: Took both drawers out. Took out the 4 bolts holding the door in place. Took old gasket off. Started in a corner placing new gasket on the door and continued around the door until gasket was completely secured onto the door. Put door back on sliding hinges and put 4 bolts back in the holes. Closed the door. Very simple.

title: Ice dispenser continued to dispense ice unless I turned it off all together
instruction: Removed the section of refrigerator that dispenses ice and water. Necessary to pry with object that does not scratch like plastic scraper. instruction: 3screws out, remove old. New one in , 3 screws . Works great so far.

title: The water dispenser lever came off, due to broken tabs in the door panel.
instruction: Before you begin, I'd recommend unplugging the refrigerator. author: MARK from CLAREMORE, OK

author: Anthony from Sarasota, IN

author: Dan from Huntington Beach, CA

author: Bridget from GREER, SC

instruction:

I got my parts the day after I ordered them.

author: Ronald from WASHINGTON, MI

author: KATHLEEN from PECONIC, NY

title: E:15 error code with Watertap
instruction:
The E:15 error code means water is detected in the pan under the unit. There are several ways this can happen.

In this case, it was caused by a bad inlet valve. It did not close properly and led to an overflow of water inside that eventually spilled into the pan underneath the unit.

I see now why the pump keeps run

author: Violet from SALEM, IL

author: Tom from CANBY, OR

author: David from Swanzey, NH

author: Charles from OLYPHANT, PA

Rubber friction sleeves on each side of the door provide resistance to prevent the door from quickly opening when unlatched. Over time the friction sleeve may crack and fail. author: Jm from OSHKOSH, WI

author: Kathey from Humboldt, TN

author: david from hull, MA

Thanks for sending genuine GE part

author: Aaron from CLARKSTON, GA

author: Steven from OXNARD, CA

Remove water line
Remove the screws on bottom left of washer to remove solenoid valve

Remove valve far enough to disconnect wire
Order correct valve assembly

Scew unit in place ,2 screws

author: Michael from CASTLE ROCK, CO

6 reverse process

author: Brian from Elkridge, MD

author: Cody from Denver, CO

instruction: The entire flat side of the end cap, (with the cutout latch), goes on the outside of the guide bar. It took less than 15 seconds to insert. It took about 30 minutes of searching for videos and playing around with the part to figure this out. A simple diagram would have been helpful.
author: Ellen from DOVER, DE

title: Dishwasher was missing a few elements . . .
instruction: Ordering was a breeze, the diagrams made it simple! Parts were ordered, parts were shipped, received and installed. Wonderfully easy.

title: ball bearings falling out of the upper dish rack
instruction: pulled the end caps, pulled the upper dish rack out. Installed the rear end cap on the right hand side of the inside slider for the rack. installed the bearing and slider in position. Put the upper rack back in and installed the front end caps.

Removed racks and replaced snap in rollers in bottom shelf and installed new stops in top rack.

No tools needed

instruction: Pulled out the rack installed new slides, rollers and endcaps,It was a snap !
author: Karl from Ke West, FL

title: Broken drawer slides
instruction:
The repair was very easy, I just had to replace some bad bearing slides in the drawer pull. Remove the end cap, remove the top drawer, remove the old bearing slide from the drawer slide and snap the new one in. finally replacing the end caps.
Ordering the parts was easy and delivery was fast.
author: steve from ramsey, MN

instruction:

Under Dishwasher:
Removed water feed connection.
On top of Dishwasher:
Removed screws anchoring it to cabinet.
Pulled dishwasher out and flipped down so it’s resting on the front.
Removed drain hose on drain pump.

author: Nicole from APPLETON, WI

author: Carolyn from TUCSON, AZ

author: Ryan from Rochester, IN

author: Bruce from HUNTINGTN BCH, CA

title: Not draining

title: Dishwasher would not drain

author: Kevin from BOZEMAN, MT

author: George from FARRAGUT, TN

author: Bill from PORT ORCHARD, WA

Removed the cover at the front bottom to gain access to the nuts holding on the element.
Turned off dishwasher breaker.
Removed the wires connected to the element.
With a 1/2" wrench, removed the element mounting screws.
Removed the bottom rack.
Removed the lower spray arm.
Removed the element from 2 clips.

author: James from CHERRY TREE, PA

Also had to lube them with silicone to get the element back
author: Eric from Holly, MI

title: dishwasher was leaking at heating element connections
instruction: Both heating element brass nuts had a split in them. They had fallen off the heating element and were hanging on the electrical wires. I removed the wires from the heating element and removed the brass nuts from the wires. I then screwed the new nuts on the heating element and reattached the wires. problem solved. I want to thank you for
author: John from Metairie, LA

title: Heating Element Seal and Nut
instruction: Never worked on a dishwasher before but quickly learned that on this particular one, it's only this thin little brass nut that tightens down the element from the underside of the washer. author: Bryan from Charlotte, NC

title: Brass nuts holding heating element in place had split
instruction: All you have to do power down the unit, then disconnect the power connections at the element and remove the old nuts and replace them with the new ones and tighten. Don't tighten too much, the element has a rubber seal that just needs the nut to snug it up.

title: heater element burnt out (black spot)
instruction:
Make sure power is off. Remove metal toe kick with fillips screw driver. Reach under dishwasher with 1/2" open
end wrench and completly unscrew brass nuts from element ends. Then open door and pull element ends straight up. Note: As you pull element ends up (inside washer) you are also forcing the element end wire connectors to come
author: Wendell from Madisonville, TN

author: bill from spokane valley, WA

instruction: I removed the top pulled out oil soaked insulation then decided to clean some of the parts Broke a torx screw on the burner then striped the tube and the burner so had to order the new parts and then put everything back together and it works fine again..It was my fault and the stove has not given me any problems..

instruction:
The ignitor switches are installed on top of the 4 gas valves for the range top. These switches control the electronic ignition. To replace the switch assembly the top of the range must be removed to gain access.

author: Michael from Dardanelle, AR

author: Patricia from Allen, TX

author: John from SAN JOSE, CA

author: Charles from Melrose Park, IL

instruction: After pulling dishwasher out both springs easily installed using plastic connectors on the bottom left and right sides. Pliars were used to stretch the springs. It took fifteen minutes at most.

author: kathleen from farmersville, CA

During the above, the plastic face of the door fell off, which created a nuisance task before proceeding to fix the original problem. However, while replacing the
author: Louis from CHESTERFIELD, MO

title: detergent dispenser would not operate
instruction: remove star screws holding inside door panel. remove plastic cover that protects latch assembly. hook one end of spring on stationary pin on inside of slider bar. Hook other end of spring on pin on slider bar. replace cover and door panel.
author: Lee from Thomaston, GA

title: Long spring broke that pulls soap cup open
instruction: Opened the door by using a star screwdriver. Pulled the door inside from the outside. Located the broken spring, put in new one (be very carefull to see how the insides are put together..makes life ALOT easier), and carefully put back together.
author: mark from ickesburg, PA

title: Detergent Cup does not open
instruction: Disconnect power supply to dishwasher. Open door and remove screws on inner door cover. Carefully remove inner cover while watching how inner parts are arranged. Found return spring on detergent cup linkage had rusted and broken causing detergent cup not to open. Installed new spring and re assembled inner cover. Rotated timer dial one fu
author: stephen from venice, FL

title: Dishwasher door very heavy to lift or drop down due to broken spring.
instruction: Was very easy to replace broken spring which required each end of spring to be reconnected to bracket located on the door and frame of the dishwasher. Was able to complete without moving the entire dishwasher frame.
author: RUDOLPH from NORWALK, CT

title: Detergent cup failed to open
instruction: Originally the dishwasher started to leak. I determined that it was coming from the door and upon further inspection found that the latch for the detergent cup seal was bad. I replaced that and the leak stopped however the lid would not open to dispense the detergent. So I also replaced the wax motor to correct that as well.
author: PETER from CROWN POINT, IN

title: both springs broke on washer door
instruction: Well, I thought I was going to have to pull the whole dishwasher out and disconnect the supply line and drain line, but I didn't. I just took off the bottom plate, got a flashlight and got on my back on the floor, then by feel I put the plastic spring linkage piece on the door hinges, then by feel I connected the spring to the other end
author: Daniel from Denton, TX

title: Springs that held up door were broken
instruction: I unscrewed the dishwasher brackets (2 of them) from under the counter, slid out the dishwasher. The springs (or broken springs) were visible. I removed them, popped the new ones in and viola!!! The door sprung up like it was new. Of course I slid the dishwasher back under the counter and put the screws back in. This took 15 minutes.
author: Nydia from Howell, NJ

title: door stayed fully open
instruction: unscrewd screws at the top; grasp the inside top, lifted & pulled out far enough to view springs; checked way they were fastened as there are several holes fot the springs; using pliers, replaced old with the new
author: Mary L from Fallbrook, CA

title: Door Springs worn
instruction:
First: I unplugged the dishwasher.

Second: I removed the two screws that hold the dishwasher in place under the counter.

Third: I pulled the dishwasher out in order to see the sides of the doors where the springs hold the door attached to the dishwasher.

Fourth: I removed the worn springs with needle nose
author: Ester from LA QUINTA, CA

title: The door springs had worn out.
instruction: Removed the bottom plate beneath the dishwasher door and the two top screws that held the dishwasher in place. Pulled the dishwasher out from the cabinets and removed the old springs. Attached the new springs to the linkage and slide the dishwasher back in place. Reattached the bottom plate and the two top screws. Done!
author: Jeffery from Waleska, GA

title: Broken dishwasher door spring
instruction: Remove the screws securing dishwasher to cabinetry; slide the machine out; hook spring into chassis; stretch spring using pliers and attach to arm on washer door. Push the machine back into place, replace screws. Very easy. The spring was delivered in about two days. Piece of cake.
author: John from West hurley, NY

title: Water leaking underneath dishwasher
instruction: went online to parts select. Looked at parts that could be leaking. Thought it was the sump. Purchased the sump and the pump connector. Hardest part was getting the dishwa
author: Anthony from East Islip, NY

title: water leaking from sump
instruction: I had a slow leak from vicinity of sump. I replaced sump and pump connector as these were only likely sources of leak based on parts select history. Turns out plastic tub had a fine crack. The crack was directly under the heating element which had melted the plastic and over time created this small crack that was found by a repair guy

author: Jim K from Whittier, CA

author: Ashraf from Merrick, NY

author: william from sykesville, MD

instruction: i removed the screw holding the drain pump to the wire that held the pump to the dishwasher frame, i then unscrewed the hose clamps that connected the pump to the drain hose and the other part of the dishwasher i disconnected the wires , put the other pump into place wired it up and now my dishwasher is as good as new .

author: Missy from BOWDLE, SD

author: Jeff from Downingtown, PA

author: RANDALL from TUCSON, AZ

title: the nut holding on the element would not tighten. leaked at the location where the nut was located
instruction:
Removed the cover at the front bottom to gain access to the nuts holding on the element.
Turned off dishwasher breaker.
Removed the wires connected to the element.
With a 1/2" wrench, removed the element mounting screws.
Removed the bottom rack.
Removed the lower spray arm.
Removed the element from 2 clips.

Unplug the wires going into the motor and replace the motor with the new one. But you need to replace the grommet the motor shaft slides up into or it will still leak.

instruction: After shutting off electricity, lay dishwasher on it's side (use a towel to absorb any water) then just use nut driver to remove faulty valve.

Remove two front mount screws from counter top
Lower dishwasher floor feets
Pulled electric leads cover and disconnect electric leads
Pulled dishwasher out and leaned on it's back
Sorry missed a step turn off breaker to dishwasher
Removed water line and drain hose
Removed motor/pump using only a socket setup

author: JIMMY from BURNET, TX

It was actually really closer to four hours.

author: John from Traverse City, MI

author: Brian M. from Hereford, AZ

author: Betty from Saluda, VA

Cleaned up the area where the unit was, Installed the new unit, tightened the clamps and it was done. Probably took around an hour because of my cleaning up the sealing areas.

title: Old recirc pump failed
instruction:
It is a bit difficult to align the grommet, hose, and mounting arm. Suggest using a little vasoline in bushing for the mounting arm/support. it really helps slide in the arm into that bushing so you can get the grommet and hose lined up.

Also, instead of using the supplied hose clamp, suggest using an automotive style hose

I removed the main pump leaving the wire terminals in place so I could energize the pump out side of the dishwasher (cut with diagonal cutter). I energized the pump and found that it ran. I noticed
author: Peter from TOLEDO, OH

author: Kenneth from PAHRUMP, NV

Slid in the new ones and found that the retaining strip would not work without replacing the inner strip. I didn't want to order this $53 dollar plastic strip so I squeezed a couple of rubber pieces into the bottom of the side edges to hold the top panel.

I needed to cut 1/4inch off the panel and unscrew the side piece which held it in place....
insert the new piece and put back the 3 screws. Done!

All I had to do was remove old door panel and retainer and I replaced with the new.
PartSelect were great. I highly recommend you guys.

I pried off the damaged bright trim from the left side of the door, scraping off most of the glue residue with a knife
author: George from Denville, NJ

instruction: easy as long as you have the right tool to take the panel off, maybe they could include one for people who don't have a good selection of tools. Thankfully we did.

author: James from North Hollywood, CA

author: Debbie from Lilburn, GA

author: Lois from New Richmond, WI

author: mike from lockport, NY

instruction: Very simple. Remove bottom panels. Remove one screw holding old switch in place. Move wire connections from old switch to new one. Cleaned and lubed the switch actuator. author: James from AMISSVILLE, VA

author: Clifford from Palm Harbor, FL

author: George from Duluth, GA

author: Thomas from Leesburg, VA

author: Ray from LAWRENCEVILLE, NJ

author: Glenn from FULSHEAR, TX

instruction:
locate lock tab and gently press
slide off the old assembly.
align and slide the new assembly on.

the lock tab is sometimes hard to push in, if you struggle with pushing it you can either break it off the old assembly or use a small flat head screwdriver to gain leverage.

author: Joel from NEW YORK, NY

instruction:
Replacing the rear wheel assembly isn't as easy as replacing the front, which took 5 minutes. You have to align the tine row, so it takes a few minutes more. But I'm a tiny woman with long nails, and if I can do it, you can do it!

Just watch the video, follow the directions, and you can't go wrong.

author: Lenora from EMMETSBURG, IA

instruction:
Remove any pieces of the rear stop by prying it off the end with small flat blade screwdriver. Make sure rack is fully on the roller tracks and then carefully push the new plastic end piece onto the rack. Be sure to orient it correctly by checking the end piece of the other rack.
I ordered two and replace them both at the same time.

title: The rack stop clip on the upper right rail broke. I ordered two replacements and installed the part in about 15 minutes!
instruction: I pulled the upper rack out of the dishwasher. I then removed the broken rack clip stop on the right side and reinstalled the new replacement clip. I then put the rack back onto the rollers and voila, the upper rack no longer fell down off of the tracks!! Problem solved and the replacement clip only cost $8.95!!

author: LOUIS from RAYNE, LA

instruction:

The source of the problem looks more like the door latch because I use to push the door in to get it going before I replace the parts.

author: ANTENEH B from EAST GRANBY, CT

author: MICHAEL from ORLEANS, IN

author: Joe from Waxhaw, NC

author: Dennis from AUBURNDALE, WI

author: mike from lockport, NY

Penelope

author: Kathryn from STAFFORD, VA

author: Gene from STONEHAM, MA

author: Mitchell from NEW ROCHELLE, NY

Followed the video from PartSelect. I've used PartSelect for replacement parts three times now, and their videos do an excellent job of showing how to do the repair.

Three tries, three times waiting for parts but the result was good.

author: Anthony j from congers, NY

author: Brad from Woodbury, MN

title: Touch pad on dishwasher dead
instruction:
1. Remove the two screws that attach the bottom cover.
2. Remove the 2 screws that attach the door outer cover.
3. Remove the 8 screws that attache the door inner cover.
4. Remove the plastic cover over the electronic controller.
5. Remove the two connections to the thermal fuse.
6. Remove the thermal fuse.

title: Door leaking
instruction:
Float switch right in front. Did not remove dishwasher. Used small flat screwdriver to un clip cover. Very soft and easy. Unplug and it slides out.
Same with the water inlet. Did not remove and used a screwdriver and small channel locks. Turn off water. Remove hose and remove screw. Slides out. Very easy.

author: Dennis from AUBURNDALE, WI

author: mike from lockport, NY

instruction: Very simple. Remove bottom panels. Remove one screw holding old switch in place. Move wire connections from old switch to new one. Cleaned and lubed the switch actuator. author: James from AMISSVILLE, VA

author: Clifford from Palm Harbor, FL

I removed the two plates located below the dishwasher door to expose the float switch. I removed the two screws holding float switch, I removed screw holding switch actuator, then I removed float assembly.

author: Bob from Allen, TX

author: michael from cambridge, MA

author: George from Duluth, GA

Replaced the middle spray arm kit and the upper spray arm mount. Also replaced worn out spring for the soap dish.
Now all areas of the dishwasher get cleaned and the soap dispenses correctly every time.

author: John from SAN JOSE, CA

author: Carl from SUMMERFIELD, FL

author: Kyle from MIDLOTHIAN, VA

The first try didn't go well. The door didn't stay locked because the new seal was preventing it.

author: Andre from Sugar Land, TX

author: Kevin from Port Orchard, WA

instruction: Installed the new tub gasket, fairly simple. Installed the bottom door seal not so easy. Leaks are still present.
author: Brian from LOS ALAMOS, NM

title: My new rubber gasket did not have a white line like stated but I figured it out after studing it a few times.
instruction: Once I figured it out it was not bad at all and most of all it worked, no leaks. I just cleaned some old glue off the stainless steel, dried it well, ran a bead of glue like directions showed, squeezed in the new gasket, closed the door for 24 hours then ran the dishwasher. No Problems.
author: John from SOUTH LYON, MI

title: Dishwaster was leaking when running.
instruction: 1. Removed lower dish tray. 2. Removed old gasket by pulling it out. Came out easy. 3. Cleaned gasket track of food particles with toothbrush and rag. 4. Found center of new gasket and installed new gasket by starting at the top center and work around track pushing gasket in until seated. 5. Tested and no leaks.

title: Door pops open easily
instruction: We have been living with this problem for a couple of years. My wife resorted to leaning a chair with a bag of potatoes against the door. author: Martin from Raleigh, NC

title: Water Leaking
instruction: Cleaned area, applied sealant and laid the sealant in. Unfortunately, it did not work. Still leaks. Going to the maytag store to get another and try again.
author: Susan from Prairie du Sac, WI

title: Steam leaking from inner seal of door
instruction: Inner gasket (Part # PS16221119) was angled in at the corners, so it wouldn't make a seal with the door, resulting in steam leakage and damage to adjacent cabinet door. Simply pulled out old gasket, pushed new one into track and voila, problem solved. New gasket angles out at corners, creating steam-tight seal.

title: Replaced door skin from factory black to new stainless steel
instruction: Unscrew 6 Torx screws and slip/slide down and off outer door panel. Take off old insulation and place it into interior of new door skin. Slide new sin into place and allow clips to engage to snug. Retighten 6 Torx screws.

title: This did not fix the rack issue
instruction: It was wrong part. Visual in diagram does not clearly show what needs to be replaced. Old part just broke so we do not know what needs fixing.

author: Mark from TEHACHAPI, CA

instruction: I watched a U Tube video about banging sound from dryer. Once I recognized the problem, lifted the top, removed 2 screws holding the front, removed the drum, and bingo. Saw the worn out drum roller. Ordered the replacement parts from "PartSelect" on line (Great Company). Was in no hurry, so I chose regular mail delivery. 4 days later, got
author: Larry from S ROCKWOOD, MI

title: Door keeps opening while operating
instruction: Removed old catch and strike with screwdriver and needle nose pliers. Installed new parts. My old catch did not have comparible numbers so I just used the yellow one. Worked fine.
author: Carmine from MASSAPEQUA PK, NY

title: Dryer door latch broke and door wouldn’t stay shut.
instruction: Jimmied out the latch using two screw drivers to get under the edges. Pushed the new piece in. Voila! Took 2 minutes for what my repair man told me would cost about $200 to fix. Unbelievable!!( I first watched some YouTube videos to get the idea )
author: Susan from WARREN, NJ

title: Dryer door wouldn't catch and stay shut
instruction: I take the screws out of the door, I removed the catch from behind inside the dryer door, I slid the new catch in the door and snapped it in place. After getting a new catch in the door I put the door back together and put the screws in. Easy repair
author: Melody from TEXARKANA, TX

title: Broken dryer door catch
instruction: Followed the video instructions which were comprehensive, easily understood, and prefaced with a listing of necessary tools. Completely satisfied with parts and supplementary information.
author: Kenneth from UPPR MARLBORO, MD

title: The door cables broke and latch was warn to the point of being too loose
instruction: This model top can be popped off after removing the two screws under the lint filter. Once exposed remove the old cables and feed them through the hole on the front panel. Feed the springs through the ends of the cables and hook the other end into the dryer side panel slots towards the top on each side. Once both cables are fed, feed t
author: Wiley from LIVONIA, MI

title: first latch broke, then appliance wouldn't start
instruction: First I ordered and replaced latch assembly...very easy and straight forward. When dw wouldn't start I ordered a door switch which I observed was worn down. After that, everything works like new. Instructional video was perfect! Just follow the steps, go slow, and don't over tighten. Easy! Total cost less than $80.
author: Craig from LK HAVASU CTY, AZ

title: Door latch not working
instruction: Watch a YouTube video to replace the latch. The strike, removes easily by gently prying out with a screw driver on both sides. You do NOT have to pull out the dishwasher as some you tube videos show.
author: Michael from LONDON, KY

title: Door pops open easily
instruction: We have been living with this problem for a couple of years. My wife resorted to leaning a chair with a bag of potatoes against the door. As time went on, she had to use heaver and heaver potatoes. Soon, nothing would hold the door shut. As a last resort (after calling Kitchen Aid and finding out my extended warranty that was paid for 5 y
author: Martin from Raleigh, NC

title: Door would not remain closed stopping the cycle.
instruction: After replacing the door latch which was not faulty I learned fron a local appliance repair company the door was distorted as a result of an earlier failure of the cable assembly breaking. The door opened with such great force hiting my leg and apparently distorted the door or machine frame. The fix was to bundle a towel and place it be
author: David from New Baltimore, MI

title: Lights flashing, wouldn't turn on
instruction: First changed motherboard and door switch, which didn't fix the problem. Inspected door latch and saw that one of the tabs was broken. Replaced latch and problem solved.
author: chris from Novato, CA

title: Door Pops open when running
instruction: I changed the Springs,Cables,Hinges (both) also changed both latches one on the door and the striker on the top of the tub. Problem still exists. Call worldpool today they never heard of this issue but if you google kitchenaid Dishwasher door pops open you get all kinds of hits.. You guys were great no problem with the parts..
author: Robert from Coral Springs, FL

title: latch pops open on door during cycle...
instruction:
Replaced strike plate...but may not have needed it ...He used a screw under the front of the strike plate as a wedge to increase tension...He said this has happened to this model before and an old tech told him about this fix...
It must be a defect in the model that after a while the strike plate needs more tension..sent unopened ,u
author: Linda from Laguna Niguel, CA

title: Unit started only intermittently and then finally fail to start at all.
instruction: Unplugged unit from power source.Removed the screws fastening the interior panel to the door. Removed latch assembly from the door after disconnecting two wires to the microswitch. Removed microswitch from the latch assembly, then installed same microswitch in new latch assembly. Re-connected wires and re-installed latch assembly. Re-inst
author: Joseph from Gilroy, CA

title: Heat dry not working. Heavy duty cycle not working.
instruction: Remove front top panel. Unplug 4 sets wires. Remove control panel with tiny wrench socket. Install new control panel. Reattach wires & replace tip front panel.
author: Richard from CUMMING, GA

title: Bought lower rack, but discovered we didn't need it. Ordered the tine rack instead.
instruction: Our experience was amazing. The part itself simply needed to be replaced: dropped into the lower rack and it was done. The amazing part was the wonderful service that this site provided. We discovered our initial mistake, contacted the company, and received instructions for how to return it. Then we ordered the tine and it was sent im
author: Susan from Bath, ME

title: Broken bottom rack
instruction: Removed old rack and and removed old rollers and installed old rollers on new rack as they work better than the new rollers sent with new rack
author: Charles from CONVOY, OH

title: Rack tines were corroded
instruction: Took off the old wheels and placed them on the new rack - fast and easy if you watch the video.
author: J Kevin from Pittsburg, CA

title: Lower dish rack needed replaced
instruction: Removed new from box and installed rollers as instructed that's all there was , very easy.
author: Lester from HARLINGEN, TX

title: Broken cheap plastic wheels lower rack
instruction: Popped out old wheel housing. Popped in replacement with a little help from a flathead screwdriver. Easy.
author: Peter from WESTMONT, IL

title: Old rack had rusted out
instruction: Replaced the old rack with a new one. Saved about $30.
author: Justin from Fort Wayne, IN

title: The upper & lower rack was rusted and broken in several areas.
instruction: It was easy! First I ordered the expensive replacement parts on line. The parts arrived in one week. I was able to slide the old drawers out, slip a few parts off of the old drawers, snap them on and slide the new drawers in place!
author: Joseph from Mission Viejo, CA

title: Replace lower dishwasher rack due to broken tines
instruction: Although the lower rack was a slightly different style than our original, it fit the dishwasher perfectly. We needed to transfer the silverware racks to the new rack and insert one set of removable tines. About 5 minutes and we are very happy with the repair.
author: Daniel from River Falls, WI

title: Lower rack was rusting, staining dishes.
instruction: Rolled out old, rolled in new.
author: Hugh from ESCONDIDO, CA

title: Hose threads stripped
instruction: I found it best to lay the dishwasher on it's side, this makes it easier to attach a 90 degree hose fitting without cross threading the plastic fitting.
author: Matthew from N KINGSTOWN, RI

title: Inlet valve leaking at water connection
instruction: The valve has a plastic fitting to attach the the water line with a hose fitting. Was not carful enough with the original and damaged it attaching the water line. Ordered a replacement fitting. While it is possible to replace the water inlet valve without pulling the dishwasher out from the cabinet found it was easier to get at with the m
author: Joseph from BIRMINGHAM, MI

title: Water was leaking from the inlet at all times
instruction:
1. Cut power to dishwasher
2. Cut water to dishwasher
3. Remove two screws that secure panel under door
4. Remove door and insulation behind it
5. Inlet valve assembly is located just behind panel on the left side
6. With your hand, press the tab on the green terminal that holds the wire harness.
7. Disconnec
author: Colin from Mebane, NC

title: No water to dishwasher
instruction: After watching the video, shutting off the water and electric, I began my repair. First problem....the video shows the unit in the middle of the floor and set on its side.....very easy. Mine was hard wired electrically and I had a copper tube connected to the garbage disposal (not so easy). I pulled the DW out as far as possible, removed
author: Anthony from AIKEN, SC

title: Water would not pump in, thus sprayer was not working to wash dishes.
instruction: The water inlet valve was replaced and the unit completely cleaned. Perhaps the cleaning was the most important part. The mesh screen and food chopper were slightly plugged as was the top screen below the sprayer.
author: Kelly from Afton, WY

title: Water leaking from inlet valve.
instruction: Removed bottom panel to find the leak. Shut off water and removed the inlet valve. Ordered and installed the new one. Turned on water and checked for leaks. Replaced bottom panel and was back in business. Have done 5 loads with no problems.
author: Robert from BOYNTON BEACH, FL

title: Water leaking from Inlet Valve
instruction: The repair was easy enough, but getting the brass pipe thread fitting tight enough not to leak was a challenge due to the part being difficult to hold. I needed to use three layers of Teflon tape and a vise. I had to do the job twice to get the fitting tight enough.
author: Steve from BOULDER, CO

title: Door pops open when first starting.
instruction:
Replaced the water inlet valve:

Turn off the water.

If your washed is hard wired, turn off the breaker. If plugged into an outlet, unplug it. When the water line is disconnected there will be a little water from the hose. Not good to get eater in any connectors.

Remove the door covering using the star d
author: Charles from GREEN VALLEY, AZ

title: Dishwasher was making an unusual noise when trying to fill with water (it was not filling). The dishes were not clean. I was able to pinpoint the inlet valve because I manually filled it with water and it ran fine.
instruction: Turn off water. Turn off power. (I did not turn electricity off for this repair but you should to be 100% safe)Remove baseplate. Unscrew Cooper water pipe from the part you are replacing (Have towels under to catch water). Unscrew anchor screw (need nut driver for this). Slide part to right to release the metal latches holding the part to
author: Ellen from WELLS RIVER, VT

title: Water would not shut off.
instruction: Replaced inlet valve. The video explained how to do the replacement, but the demo dishwasher was out of the cabinet and on its side. In actuality, the valve can be replaced with the appliance in place by removing the panel at the bottom, but the space is very limited. The connection of the water line is the only hard part, and should b
author: Charles from CORP CHRISTI, TX

title: The water inlet valve was dripping water on my hardwood flooring.
instruction:
Because I didn't discover the leak until the ruined my flooring it was necessary to pull the dishwasher and replace 5-6 pieces the flooring.

Once the flooring was replaced it was very easy to follow the u-tube directions from your website to replace the valve. It took the handtools you recommended and about 30 mins.
author: Clarence from BREMERTON, WA

title: Leaking Dishwasher
instruction: Simple repair. Saved me hundreds
author: Alfred from Virginia Beach, VA

title: Top rack was dropping out of rollers/Slides
instruction:
This was the second part of repair. Left side was constantly falling out of the slide. I replaced the same items as above minus the gasket and screw kit. Once done, the right side was sloppy so I orders part for that side plus gasket which slid right in.
1. Removed stops on front end of Upper Dishrack Slide on both sides.

title: Water was leaking from the inlet valve
instruction:
Turn off electrical power at breaker.
Turn off the water supply at nearest valve, disconnect supply line.
Disconnect drain hose.
Remove screws securing dishwasher to underside of countertop.
Pull dishwasher out from under the countertop, and tip it to one side.
Disconnect supply line from old inlet valve.
D
author: Mark from WHITEWATER, WI

title: Inlet valve failed causing dishwasher to flood the kitchen.
instruction: Replacing the valve was easy, but removing the old one was a nightmare- old, stuck parts, awkward location, minimal work space. Old fitting that connects hose to valve could not be removed, so I had to go to a plumbing supply company to get a replacement.
author: Rob from GREENSBORO, NC

title: water filling dishwasher even when it is off
instruction: I followed the video but reversed two of the steps. The video said to remove the water line and then remove the valve. However, there was not much room to get to the water line and it was really stuck after 10+ years. So I removed the valve first and that allowed me to move it around and get a better angle to remove the water line. Fo
author: Cyrus from COLFAX, NC

title: no water to dishwasher
instruction: googled "no water to dishwasher" and got u-tube video on 3 things to look for. first was water intake valve. video then showed how to remove and install. ordered part and installed. now have water to dishwasher tom
author: thomas from JACKSON, WY

title: No water coming into dishwasher
instruction: The repair was easy in that there were no surprises due to the video. The extra time was due to not being able to pull the appliance out for easy access. It was great to have the percentage for solving the problem identified on the website.
author: Charles from WEST PALM BCH, FL

title: Water leaking out on sides and front of door. When opening door the tub was to full and would spill out.
instruction: Shut water off to dishwasher and turn power off. Remove kick plate in front. The part on my machine was on the left side. Not a lot space to get hands or tools in. Unhook water line watch for residual water , take a picture or make a mental note of how wires are hooked up and the direction of the brass coupling ( the part the water
author: Deb from COUNCIL BLFS, IA

title: Main Pump motor not turning
instruction: Disassebled diswasher to get to main pump motor, goal was to test Ohms of motor for failure. After disassembling to get to motor it freely turned and checked good per specifications. However, chopper blade connected to motor was locked up, preventing the motor from turning thus not turning the pump. During disassembley of chopper unit, t
author: Coy from Aurora, OH

title: We had banging water pipes in the house, when the dishwasher was in use.
instruction: I replaced the electric water valve (as suggested) It was in front of the unit, so it didn't need to be pulled out. I had to disconect the water line, and a by-pass line. The hard part was disconecting this rubber hose, as it was in back of the valve. Installed the part, connected the lines and two wires...No noise, works great....
author: Michael from Issaquah, WA

title: Water leak
instruction: Decided to remove diswasher from built-in space to make part changeout easier and to check drain, wiring and change out water supply line. Since we had installed ceramic tile unit was a little hard to remove. Had to adjust front height as low as possible to get out. Once unit was out parts change went smoothly. Reinstalled and ran through
author: Allen from Pinson, AL

title: Dishwasher leaking intermittently
instruction:
To perform this repair do the following:
1.) Turn off power to the dishwasher
2.) Turn off water, disconnect the water supply and drain using adj. wrench and/or nutdriver, remove any contents from inside
3.) Remove screws (2) from underside cabinet, remove kick plate from bottom by removing two (2) screws there, pull out wa
author: Erick from Cary, NC

title: My Dishwasher goit damages from broken glass jam pump and clogged drain
instruction:
Work done"
used wet vacuum to remove all water and debris from inside out side dishwasher, used we vacuum to unclog drain, Disconnected drain hose, unplug power cord, water supply line, removed dishwasher, swap all new parts, reconnected everything and done in a zap,

thank you
author: Eddy from MALIBU, CA

title: Water not heating and door would fall when opened
instruction: Watching u tube. Made it simple
author: Dirk from HAYDEN, ID

title: The GE Cafe series Dishwasher not drying dishes.
instruction:
I pulled the dish washer out and, make sure you turn off the power, disconnect the water and drain line. un screw the mounting screws.
The first thing i checked was the drain filter which was clogged. I took shop vac and sucked all the excess water out and removed the flood switch. seemed ok but you can't tell if its ok, so just r
author: Gary D. from ALBUQUERQUE, NM

title: Tripping dishwasher GFCI circuit breaker in C/B panel located in the garage.
instruction:
Part needed to fix problem is Harness,Wiring,Main. Part # 5304504853.

Trip dishwasher circuit breaker Remove front door cover,remove door handle,remove 2 electrical wire connectors from handle one will have 2 white & the other 2 black wires. Remember which goes where. Leave old harness hanging on door. Remove control board c
author: David from FORNEY, TX

title: worn out parts
instruction: remove upper rack & replace one item at a time
author: hans from VALHALLA, NY

title: manifold wore out did not hold water anymore
instruction: remove one philips screw take out manifold replace with new one put screw back in and we are done not mechanically difficult by any means
author: Irl from EMMITSBURG, MD

title: door to dishwasher would not open slowly. would slam open
instruction: connector was broken. just attached new connector to spring on each side of door. easy fix.
author: Carol from Canterbury, CT

title: Door would fall to floor
instruction: Very easy just took out two screws that held the dishwasher to counter top.Then pulled dishwasher out just far enough that both door cables are exposed.The hardest part for me was getting the spring stretched enough to clip on.This was a easy installation for most people.
author: Thomas from ELLIJAY, GA

title: Our dishwasher door would drop open and land on our feet.
instruction: My husband was able to slide the dishwasher out, and quickly replace the old connector assembly for the new ones. The old connector assembly had broken at the “rope”. Now the door opens slowly and is as good as new.
author: Amy from San Marcos, CA

title: DW door would fall when not latched
instruction:
pulled dishwasher out of cabinet, removed side panel held by screws front and back, removed broken tension rope installed new rope, replaced side panel pushed dishwasher back into cabinet and fastened
to countertop, door works like new now, (the chief cook is happy as she can be)
author: Robert from DALTON, OH

title: Hinge Cables Broke (Both), AGAIN!!
instruction: Cables have broken about every 3-6 months after original ones broke after 8 years. Removed front kick plate screws and remove kick plate, and remove two top screws holding Dishwasher to counter-top. Pull dishwasher out about 10 inches. Remove all broken parts and replace cables. Side dishwasher back in place and reinstall removed screws.
author: Blair from POTTSTOWN, PA

title: Dishwasher door would drop, cords were broken
instruction: Removed two screws (one each side) and the toe kick plate at the bottom. Slide the dishwasher out from the cabinets about 10", remove broken cord clip from door and spring. Install door clip and wrap cord around pulley , attach to spring then attach spring to door, lifting the door will help attach the spring. Do one side of the door at a
author: Vincent from FREDERICKSBRG, VA

title: Door was very heavy due to spring problem
instruction: Turn off the power at breaker box. Disconnect the power at dishwasher since I needed to pull the unit all the way out of the cabinet to get to screws on the back side for this model. Find and remove the screws to the cover. Remove cover. In my case, the rope on the connector assembly had snapped. I replaced spring and connector identicall
author: Greg S from BELLE ISLE, FL

title: Door return
instruction: Replaced it . Simple
author: William from BREWER, ME

title: Front door would fall open without resistance.
instruction: The repair took right at one hour. Repair length of time will depend on what all you have to disconnect to get your dish washer out so you can remove both side panels where you will be able to access the door springs, etc. There is a door spring on each side and I recommend replacing both connectors cords while you have the dishwasher o
author: Ed from COHUTTA, GA

title: Door spring connector
instruction: Pull the dishwasher out from underneath the countertop took 2 minutes unscrewed the panel on the side one minute put the connector on one minute screwed the panel back on 1 minute put the dishwasher back underneath the counter two minutes very easy job
author: Thomas from Palm coast, FL

title: Door flopping down hard
instruction:
I removed the anchor screws at the top of the dishwasher, and the screws holding the bottom kickplate in place. I pulled out the dishwasher 8-10 inches to expose the cables where the plastic hinge arm links are installed.
On mine, there is a steel cable with a hook crimped on the end. The hinge arm link doesn't slide out of this crim
author: Robert from ATLANTA, GA

title: Plastic coupling broke on door cable counter balance
instruction: Removed dishwasher from under counter. Removed both cable pulleys and bushings. Threaded new cables and remounted pulleys and bushings. Finally stretched springs onto cables. Checked counter balance and reinstalled dishwasher.
author: Todd from DALLAS, TX

title: Plastic hinge arm link broke
instruction: Squeeze the new link to the cable hook with pliers while locking the vise grip to the cable for easier handling. Then, using the vise grip on the cable, hook the other end of the link to the dishwasher door hook
author: Eric from EAST MEADOW, NY

title: Hinge arm link wore out
instruction: Used Phillips screwdriver to undo brackets that keep dishwasher in place. Pulled out dishwasher from underneath the counter. Placed hinge arm in spring, hooked spring onto clip, placed hinge arm in clip. Put back dishwasher under the counter and screwed in place. Took all of 15 minutes. Saved 185.00 for service call.
author: Samuel from LAS VEGAS, NV

title: The door dropped all the way down
instruction: The repair itself was simple. I replaced the broken plastic pulley and the cable attached to the door and spring because one end was bent. I also had to remove the fitting that held the pulley in place. In order to access the spring, I had to pull the dishwasher way out and that required disconnecting the water supply, the drain tube, a
author: Dennis from GETTYSBURG, PA

title: Broken spring on door.
instruction: See GE web site for repair instructions. Take out screws at top of door. Slide unit out there is a spring on each side of the door just look at the good one for details. Easy fix. About 30 minutes.
author: Ron from SOUTHPORT, NC

title: plastic hinge arm link broke causing door to flop open
instruction: First I had to unscrew screws under the counter then pulled built in dishwasher out from under the counter, attached hing arm link to right side bracket on door, and the other end I attatched to a spring at the back of the unit. Thats it! and pushed the dishwasher back into place. All back to normal....by the way Im a 67 yr old great gra

author: Lonnie from YUKON, OK

title: Cable had come off of roller
instruction: First went to U Tube to view installation instructions and location of part. It was fairly easy to replace since I had installed the unit. I was able to move the unit out enough without disconnecting any line since there was enough slack in all three connections, only shut the power off. This was a very easy replacement.

author: Jonathan from ABINGDON, VA

author: Daniel from FAIR OAKS, CA

author: William from AUSTIN, TX

author: Bonnie from South Orange, NJ

author: Eliana from SCHAUMBURG, IL

author: JOHN from MARYSVILLE, WA
